    B b;
}

class B {
    String name;
    A a;
}
```
For brevity I&#39;m using just fields -- you should write these with private fields and getters.

Then `equals/hashcode` looks like:
```
class A {
  ...
    @Override
    public boolean equals(Object o) {
        if (this == o) return true;
        if (o == null || getClass() != o.getClass()) return false;
        B b = (B) o;
        return Objects.equals(name, b.name) &amp;&amp; Objects.equals(a.name, b.a.name);
    }

    @Override
    public int hashCode() {
        return Objects.hash(name, a.name);
    }
}
```
Removing the recursion. `B` needs the same treatment.

Of course having this relationship means that if you add or remove a field from `B` you need to change `A`&#39;s `equals/hashcode` implementations.

If you know (because of the way you construct your A and B instances) the `x.equals(y)` implies `x == y` for all instances of `A` and `B` then you can simplify your implementations by using reference equality.

